cells, literally-- this

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:15.260 align:middle line:84%
isn't a metaphor--
literally, is the equivalent

00:18:15.260 --> 00:18:20.070 align:middle line:84%
of a microcircuit, a
nano circuit, almost.

00:18:20.070 --> 00:18:22.720 align:middle line:84%
It is the equivalent
of a gated circuit.

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:23.520 align:middle line:90%
You have an input.

00:18:23.520 --> 00:18:24.510 align:middle line:90%
You have an output.

00:18:24.510 --> 00:18:27.440 align:middle line:84%
There are components within
the cell that do all the things

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:28.470 align:middle line:90%
that a circuit does.

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:30.200 align:middle line:10%
We have components
in our cells that

00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:32.520 align:middle line:10%
are the equivalent of
transistors, of resistors,

00:18:32.520 --> 00:18:33.840 align:middle line:10%
of capacitors.

00:18:33.840 --> 00:18:34.723 align:middle line:90%
And I'm smiling--

00:18:34.723 --> 00:18:37.140 align:middle line:84%
>> REGINA: Transferring of
some information is astounding.

00:18:37.140 --> 00:18:38.220 align:middle line:84%
>> BRADEN: Well it
is, I'm smiling.

00:18:38.220 --> 00:18:40.380 align:middle line:84%
I did this with a group
recently, a live group,

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:41.755 align:middle line:90%
and they were very young people.

00:18:41.755 --> 00:18:43.880 align:middle line:84%
When I say young, they were
in their teens and 20s.

00:18:43.880 --> 00:18:44.730 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: What's a transistor?

00:18:44.730 --> 00:18:47.063 align:middle line:84%
>> BRADEN: And I had pictures
of transistors, resistors,

00:18:47.063 --> 00:18:48.170 align:middle line:90%
and capacitors.

00:18:48.170 --> 00:18:49.520 align:middle line:90%
And they said, what are those?

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:51.530 align:middle line:84%
And then the next picture
was a microcircuit.

00:18:51.530 --> 00:18:53.197 align:middle line:84%
And they said, oh,
we know what that is.

00:18:53.197 --> 00:18:55.687 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, all of
these now fit on that micro.

00:18:55.687 --> 00:18:57.020 align:middle line:90%
And they said, OK, I'm with you.

00:18:57.020 --> 00:18:57.820 align:middle line:90%
I'm with you now.

00:18:57.820 --> 00:18:59.600 align:middle line:84%
But that happened
just in our lifetime.

00:18:59.600 --> 00:19:00.400 align:middle line:90%
That's how fast.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:01.720 align:middle line:90%
But it doesn't stop there.

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:06.620 align:middle line:84%
Because every cell emits
photons, particles of light.

00:19:06.620 --> 00:19:08.960 align:middle line:10%
Every cell receives
photons, particles of light.

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:10.480 align:middle line:90%
Light is information.

00:19:10.480 --> 00:19:13.510 align:middle line:84%
So we are constantly
in dialogue,

00:19:13.510 --> 00:19:16.340 align:middle line:84%
in communication with one
another in the world around us.

00:19:16.340 --> 00:19:17.960 align:middle line:84%
We may not know
what we're saying,

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:19.760 align:middle line:84%
but we're sending
that information.

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:23.140 align:middle line:84%
Every cell stores information
and retrieves information, just

00:19:23.140 --> 00:19:24.632 align:middle line:84%
the way we do on
a computer chip.

00:19:24.632 --> 00:19:26.590 align:middle line:84%
I'm just going to share
a couple more of these,

00:19:26.590 --> 00:19:28.910 align:middle line:90%
because it's a mind blower.

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:32.350 align:middle line:84%
The DNA in the
nucleus of every cell

00:19:32.350 --> 00:19:36.700 align:middle line:84%
holds a record of every
successful genetic transaction

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:38.710 align:middle line:90%
of our entire species.

00:19:38.710 --> 00:19:41.300 align:middle line:84%
Now, listen to the words
that are being used.

00:19:41.300 --> 00:19:43.610 align:middle line:10%
That record is transparent.

00:19:43.610 --> 00:19:46.630 align:middle line:10%
It is immutable,
and it's secure.

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:48.970 align:middle line:10%
And if that sounds familiar
to any of our viewers,

00:19:48.970 --> 00:19:52.590 align:middle line:10%
it's because those are exactly
the terms being used to describe

00:19:52.590 --> 00:19:53.955 align:middle line:10%
blockchain technology.

00:19:53.955 --> 00:19:54.973 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Bitcoin, yep.

00:19:54.973 --> 00:19:57.390 align:middle line:84%
>> BRADEN: Bitcoin was the
first example of the blockchain

00:19:57.390 --> 00:20:02.390 align:middle line:84%
technology, because that
external technology is built

00:20:02.390 --> 00:20:03.190 align:middle line:90%
copying--

00:20:03.190 --> 00:20:05.740 align:middle line:84%
It mimics what we
already do in our bodies.

00:20:05.740 --> 00:20:07.600 align:middle line:90%
All of the external technology--

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:10.020 align:middle line:84%
I worked in the defense
industry during the Cold War

00:20:10.020 --> 00:20:15.180 align:middle line:84%
years, Star Wars Defense, SDI,
Star Wars Defense Initiative.

00:20:15.180 --> 00:20:18.308 align:middle line:84%
At that time, I saw some of
the most advanced technology,

00:20:18.308 --> 00:20:19.600 align:middle line:90%
that this world has ever known.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:21.017 align:middle line:84%
And Regina, I'm
going to tell you,

00:20:21.017 --> 00:20:25.290 align:middle line:84%
I have yet to see anything
built out there, that

00:20:25.290 --> 00:20:29.173 align:middle line:84%
doesn't mimic what we already do
in here, except we do it better.

00:20:29.173 --> 00:20:30.340 align:middle line:90%
Let me give another example.

00:20:30.340 --> 00:20:33.300 align:middle line:84%
The scientist recently
compared a human brain

00:20:33.300 --> 00:20:35.100 align:middle line:90%
to a microprocessor.

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:36.300 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: Yes, I love this.

00:20:36.300 --> 00:20:37.030 align:middle line:84%
>> BRADEN: When
people say, well,

00:20:37.030 --> 00:20:38.363 align:middle line:90%
how do you make that equivalent?

00:20:38.363 --> 00:20:39.340 align:middle line:90%
This is pretty cool.

00:20:39.340 --> 00:20:42.660 align:middle line:84%
They determined that the
average number of synapses

00:20:42.660 --> 00:20:45.020 align:middle line:84%
in the brain, the place
between the neurons, where

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:49.280 align:middle line:84%
we see that little spark jump,
the number of those synapses

00:20:49.280 --> 00:20:51.840 align:middle line:90%
happens to be about the number--

00:20:51.840 --> 00:20:53.750 align:middle line:84%
same number of
transistors that we

00:20:53.750 --> 00:20:55.920 align:middle line:84%
have on our most
advanced microprocessors.

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:57.750 align:middle line:84%
So they're calling
those the equivalents.

00:20:57.750 --> 00:20:59.420 align:middle line:10%
And the bottom line,
what they found

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:03.080 align:middle line:10%
is that the brain processes
hundredfold more efficiently

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:04.500 align:middle line:10%
than the best computers.

00:21:04.500 --> 00:21:05.570 align:middle line:90%
But listen to this.

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:08.940 align:middle line:84%
I love technology, and
computer chips, they are fast.

00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:10.230 align:middle line:90%
They are efficient.

00:21:10.230 --> 00:21:12.620 align:middle line:90%
Are they scalable?

00:21:12.620 --> 00:21:16.080 align:middle line:84%
A computer chip can only
scale to the level--

00:21:16.080 --> 00:21:19.350 align:middle line:84%
It's limited by the physics
of the stuff it's made of.

00:21:19.350 --> 00:21:22.010 align:middle line:84%
So if the silicon
chip, the information

00:21:22.010 --> 00:21:26.340 align:middle line:84%
can only move between those
silicon atoms, a certain rate,

00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:29.580 align:middle line:84%
so we say that it is
finite in its scalability.

00:21:29.580 --> 00:21:31.950 align:middle line:90%
Now, look at a human neuron.

00:21:31.950 --> 00:21:34.410 align:middle line:90%
What is our scalability?

00:21:34.410 --> 00:21:36.000 align:middle line:84%
And the answer
is, we don't know.

00:21:36.000 --> 00:21:39.860 align:middle line:84%
Because every time scientists
push a human brain,

00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:43.260 align:middle line:84%
and they push those neurons
to what they have accepted

00:21:43.260 --> 00:21:45.060 align:middle line:90%
is the limits in the past--

00:21:45.060 --> 00:21:46.060 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: We exceed it.

00:21:46.060 --> 00:21:48.400 align:middle line:84%
>> BRADEN: We do what humans
do, and here's the reason.

00:21:48.400 --> 00:21:50.020 align:middle line:84%
This is what makes
us so different.

00:21:50.020 --> 00:21:53.710 align:middle line:84%
We morph, and we adapt
to the new condition.

00:21:53.710 --> 00:21:57.070 align:middle line:84%
And we open an entire
new vista of potential.

00:21:57.070 --> 00:21:59.410 align:middle line:84%
And we do it again
and again and again.

00:21:59.410 --> 00:22:01.328 align:middle line:90%
What is our scalability?

00:22:01.328 --> 00:22:02.495 align:middle line:90%
The answer is we don't know.

00:22:02.495 --> 00:22:03.610 align:middle line:90%
>> REGINA: We don't know.

